plaid2.async_client 

   1import os
   2import aiohttp
   3import asyncio
   4import json
   5import logging
   6from .logger import logger
   7from .authenticator import PlaidAuthenticator
   8from typing import Optional, List, Any, Dict
   9from . import model
  10
  11
  12class AsyncPlaidClient:
  13    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
  14        self.authenticator = authenticator
  15        self.base_url = base_url
  16        self.session = aiohttp.ClientSession(
  17            headers={
  18                "User-Agent": "plaid2/python/0.1.0",
  19                "Content-Type": "application/json",
  20            }
  21        )
  22
  23    async def send(
  24        self,
  25        method: str,
  26        url: str,
  27        headers: Dict[str, str],
  28        params: Dict[str, str],
  29        data: Dict[str, Any],
  30    ) -> aiohttp.ClientResponse:
  31        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
  32        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
  33        if do_debug:
  34            logger.debug(
  35                json.dumps(
  36                    dict(
  37                        method=method,
  38                        url=url,
  39                        headers=dict(**headers, **self.session.headers),
  40                        params=params,
  41                        json=data,
  42                    )
  43                )
  44            )
  45        async with self.session.request(
  46            method, url, headers=headers, params=params, json=data
  47        ) as res:
  48            if do_debug:
  49                data = dict(
  50                    status_code=res.status,
  51                    headers=dict(**res.headers),
  52                )
  53                try:
  54                    data["json"] = await res.json()
  55                except json.JSONDecodeError:
  56                    data["body"] = await res.text()
  57                logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  58            if not res.ok:
  59                content = await res.text()
  60                res.release()
  61                raise aiohttp.ClientResponseError(
  62                    res.request_info,
  63                    res.history,
  64                    status=res.status,
  65                    message=content,
  66                    headers=res.headers,
  67                )
  68            return res
  69
  70    async def item_application_list(
  71        self, access_token: Optional[str] = None
  72    ) -> model.ItemApplicationListResponse:
  73        """List a users connected applications"""
  74        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
  75        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
  76        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
  77            "access_token": access_token,
  78        }
  79        res = await self.send(
  80            "POST", self.base_url + "/item/application/list", headers, params, data
  81        )
  82        data = await res.json()
  83        return model.ItemApplicationListResponse.parse_obj(data)
  84
  85    async def item_application_scopes_update(
  86        self,
  87        access_token: str,
  88        application_id: str,
  89        scopes: model.Scopes,
  90        context: str,
  91        state: Optional[str] = None,
  92    ) -> model.ItemApplicationScopesUpdateResponse:
  93        """Update the scopes of access for a particular application
  94
  95        Enable consumers to update product access on selected accounts for an application."""
  96        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
  97        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
  98        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
  99            "access_token": access_token,
 100            "application_id": application_id,
 101            "scopes": None if scopes is None else scopes.dict(),
 102            "state": state,
 103            "context": context,
 104        }
 105        res = await self.send(
 106            "POST",
 107            self.base_url + "/item/application/scopes/update",
 108            headers,
 109            params,
 110            data,
 111        )
 112        data = await res.json()
 113        return model.ItemApplicationScopesUpdateResponse.parse_obj(data)

 149    async def auth_get(
 150        self, access_token: str, options: Optional[model.AuthGetRequestOptions] = None
 151    ) -> model.AuthGetResponse:
 152        """Retrieve auth data
 153
 154        The `/auth/get` endpoint returns the bank account and bank identification numbers (such as routing numbers, for US accounts) associated with an Item's checking and savings accounts, along with high-level account data and balances when available.
 155
 156        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `auth` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the data.
 157
 158        Also note that `/auth/get` will not return data for any new accounts opened after the Item was created. To obtain data for new accounts, create a new Item.
 159
 160        Versioning note: In API version 2017-03-08, the schema of the `numbers` object returned by this endpoint is substantially different. For details, see [Plaid API versioning](https://plaid.com/docs/api/versioning/#version-2018-05-22).
 161
 162        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/auth/#authget>."""
 163        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 164        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 165        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 166            "access_token": access_token,
 167            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 168        }
 169        res = await self.send(
 170            "POST", self.base_url + "/auth/get", headers, params, data
 171        )
 172        data = await res.json()
 173        return model.AuthGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

 175    async def transactions_get(
 176        self,
 177        access_token: str,
 178        start_date: str,
 179        end_date: str,
 180        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 181    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
 182        """Get transaction data
 183
 184        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
 185
 186        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
 187
 188        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
 189
 190        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 191
 192        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
 193
 194        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
 195        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 196        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 197        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 198            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 199            "access_token": access_token,
 200            "start_date": start_date,
 201            "end_date": end_date,
 202        }
 203        res = await self.send(
 204            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
 205        )
 206        data = await res.json()
 207        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 208
 209    async def transactions_refresh(
 210        self, access_token: str
 211    ) -> model.TransactionsRefreshResponse:
 212        """Refresh transaction data
 213
 214        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
 215
 216        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
 217
 218        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
 219        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 220        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 221        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 222            "access_token": access_token,
 223        }
 224        res = await self.send(
 225            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
 226        )
 227        data = await res.json()
 228        return model.TransactionsRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
 229
 230    async def transactions_recurring_get(
 231        self,
 232        access_token: str,
 233        account_ids: List[str],
 234        options: Optional[model.TransactionsRecurringGetRequestOptions] = None,
 235    ) -> model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse:
 236        """Fetch recurring transaction streams
 237
 238        The `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint allows developers to receive a summary of the recurring outflow and inflow streams (expenses and deposits) from a users checking, savings or credit card accounts. Additionally, Plaid provides key insights about each recurring stream including the category, merchant, last amount, and more. Developers can use these insights to build tools and experiences that help their users better manage cash flow, monitor subscriptions, reduce spend, and stay on track with bill payments.
 239
 240        This endpoint is not included by default as part of Transactions. To request access to this endpoint and learn more about pricing, contact your Plaid account manager.
 241
 242        Note that unlike `/transactions/get`, `/transactions/recurring/get` will not initialize an Item with Transactions. The Item must already have been initialized with Transactions (either during Link, by specifying it in `/link/token/create`, or after Link, by calling `/transactions/get`) before calling this endpoint. Data is available to `/transactions/recurring/get` approximately 5 seconds after the [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhook has fired (about 1-2 minutes after initialization).
 243
 244        After the initial call, you can call `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint at any point in the future to retrieve the latest summary of recurring streams. Since recurring streams do not change often, it will typically not be necessary to call this endpoint more than once per day.
 245
 246        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrecurringget>."""
 247        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 248        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 249        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 250            "access_token": access_token,
 251            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 252            "account_ids": account_ids,
 253        }
 254        res = await self.send(
 255            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/recurring/get", headers, params, data
 256        )
 257        data = await res.json()
 258        return model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 259
 260    async def transactions_sync(
 261        self,
 262        access_token: str,
 263        cursor: Optional[str] = None,
 264        count: Optional[int] = None,
 265        options: Optional[model.TransactionsSyncRequestOptions] = None,
 266    ) -> model.TransactionsSyncResponse:
 267        """Get incremental transaction updates on an Item
 268
 269        This endpoint replaces `/transactions/get` and its associated webhooks for most common use-cases.
 270
 271        The `/transactions/sync` endpoint allows developers to subscribe to all transactions associated with an Item and get updates synchronously in a stream-like manner, using a cursor to track which updates have already been seen. `/transactions/sync` provides the same functionality as `/transactions/get` and can be used instead of `/transactions/get` to simplify the process of tracking transactions updates.
 272
 273        This endpoint provides user-authorized transaction data for `credit`, `depository`, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from `investments` accounts, use `/investments/transactions/get` instead.
 274
 275        Returned transactions data is grouped into three types of update, indicating whether the transaction was added, removed, or modified since the last call to the API.
 276
 277        In the first call to `/transactions/sync` for an Item, the endpoint will return all historical transactions data associated with that Item up until the time of the API call (as "adds"), which then generates a `next_cursor` for that Item. In subsequent calls, send the `next_cursor` to receive only the changes that have occurred since the previous call.
 278
 279        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. The `has_more` field specifies if additional calls are necessary to fetch all available transaction updates.
 280
 281        Whenever new or updated transaction data becomes available, `/transactions/sync` will provide these updates. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 282
 283        Note that for newly created Items, data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/sync`. Plaid begins preparing transactions data when the Item is created, but the process can take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete, depending on the number of transactions available.
 284
 285        To be alerted when new data is available, listen for the [`SYNC_UPDATES_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#sync_updates_available) webhook.
 286
 287        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionssync>."""
 288        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 289        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 290        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 291            "access_token": access_token,
 292            "cursor": cursor,
 293            "count": count,
 294            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 295        }
 296        res = await self.send(
 297            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/sync", headers, params, data
 298        )
 299        data = await res.json()
 300        return model.TransactionsSyncResponse.parse_obj(data)
 301
 302    async def institutions_get(
 303        self,
 304        count: int,
 305        offset: int,
 306        country_codes: List[str],
 307        options: Optional[model.InstitutionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 308    ) -> model.InstitutionsGetResponse:
 309        """Get details of all supported institutions
 310
 311        Returns a JSON response containing details on all financial institutions currently supported by Plaid. Because Plaid supports thousands of institutions, results are paginated.
 312
 313        If there is no overlap between an institutions enabled products and a clients enabled products, then the institution will be filtered out from the response. As a result, the number of institutions returned may not match the count specified in the call.
 314
 315        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/institutions/#institutionsget>."""
 316        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 317        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 318        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 319            "count": count,
 320            "offset": offset,
 321            "country_codes": country_codes,
 322            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 323        }
 324        res = await self.send(
 325            "POST", self.base_url + "/institutions/get", headers, params, data
 326        )
 327        data = await res.json()
 328        return model.InstitutionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

The `public_key` parameter has since been deprecated; all customers are encouraged to use `client_id` and `secret` instead.
 342
 343
 344        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/institutions/#institutionssearch>."""
 345        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 346        params: Dict[str, str] = {}

 350            "country_codes": country_codes,
 351            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 352        }
 353        res = await self.send(
 354            "POST", self.base_url + "/institutions/search", headers, params, data
 355        )
 356        data = await res.json()
 357        return model.InstitutionsSearchResponse.parse_obj(data)

 386    async def item_remove(self, access_token: str) -> model.ItemRemoveResponse:
 387        """Remove an Item
 388
 389        The `/item/remove` endpoint allows you to remove an Item. Once removed, the `access_token`, as well as any processor tokens or bank account tokens associated with the Item, is no longer valid and cannot be used to access any data that was associated with the Item.
 390
 391        Note that in the Development environment, issuing an `/item/remove`  request will not decrement your live credential count. To increase your credential account in Development, contact Support.
 392
 393        Also note that for certain OAuth-based institutions, an Item removed via `/item/remove` may still show as an active connection in the institution's OAuth permission manager.
 394
 395        API versions 2019-05-29 and earlier return a `removed` boolean as part of the response.
 396
 397        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/items/#itemremove>."""
 398        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 399        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 400        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 401            "access_token": access_token,
 402        }
 403        res = await self.send(
 404            "POST", self.base_url + "/item/remove", headers, params, data
 405        )
 406        data = await res.json()
 407        return model.ItemRemoveResponse.parse_obj(data)
 408
 409    async def accounts_get(
 410        self,
 411        access_token: str,
 412        options: Optional[model.AccountsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 413    ) -> model.AccountsGetResponse:
 414        """Retrieve accounts
 415
 416        The `/accounts/get` endpoint can be used to retrieve a list of accounts associated with any linked Item. Plaid will only return active bank accounts  that is, accounts that are not closed and are capable of carrying a balance.
 417        For items that went through the updated account selection pane, this endpoint only returns accounts that were permissioned by the user when they initially created the Item. If a user creates a new account after the initial link, you can capture this event through the [`NEW_ACCOUNTS_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/items/#new_accounts_available) webhook and then use Link's [update mode](https://plaid.com/docs/link/update-mode/) to request that the user share this new account with you.
 418
 419        This endpoint retrieves cached information, rather than extracting fresh information from the institution. As a result, balances returned may not be up-to-date; for realtime balance information, use `/accounts/balance/get` instead. Note that some information is nullable.
 420
 421        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/accounts/#accountsget>."""
 422        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 423        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 424        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 425            "access_token": access_token,
 426            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 427        }
 428        res = await self.send(
 429            "POST", self.base_url + "/accounts/get", headers, params, data
 430        )
 431        data = await res.json()
 432        return model.AccountsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

 517

 519
 520        Note that this endpoint is provided for developer ease-of-use and is not required for testing webhooks; webhooks will also fire in Sandbox under the same conditions that they would in Production or Development.

 671        }

 673            "POST",
 674            self.base_url + "/identity_verification/create",
 675            headers,
 676            params,

To limit accounts listed in Link to types and subtypes supported by Liabilities, you can use the `account_filters` parameter when [creating a Link token](https://plaid.com/docs/api/tokens/#linktokencreate).
1472
1473        The types of information returned by Liabilities can include balances and due dates, loan terms, and account details such as original loan amount and guarantor. Data is refreshed approximately once per day; the latest data can be retrieved by calling `/liabilities/get`.
1474
1475        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `liabilities` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the additional data.

1595    async def payment_initiation_payment_create(
1596        self,
1597        recipient_id: str,
1598        reference: str,
1599        amount: model.PaymentAmount,
1600        schedule: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentScheduleRequest] = None,
1601        options: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentOptions] = None,
1602    ) -> model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse:
1603        """Create a payment
1604
1605        After creating a payment recipient, you can use the `/payment_initiation/payment/create` endpoint to create a payment to that recipient.  Payments can be one-time or standing order (recurring) and can be denominated in either EUR or GBP.  If making domestic GBP-denominated payments, your recipient must have been created with BACS numbers. In general, EUR-denominated payments will be sent via SEPA Credit Transfer and GBP-denominated payments will be sent via the Faster Payments network, but the payment network used will be determined by the institution. Payments sent via Faster Payments will typically arrive immediately, while payments sent via SEPA Credit Transfer will typically arrive in one business day.
1606
1607        Standing orders (recurring payments) must be denominated in GBP and can only be sent to recipients in the UK. Once created, standing order payments cannot be modified or canceled via the API. An end user can cancel or modify a standing order directly on their banking application or website, or by contacting the bank. Standing orders will follow the payment rules of the underlying rails (Faster Payments in UK). Payments can be sent Monday to Friday, excluding bank holidays. If the pre-arranged date falls on a weekend or bank holiday, the payment is made on the next working day. It is not possible to guarantee the exact time the payment will reach the recipients account, although at least 90% of standing order payments are sent by 6am.
1608
1609        In the Development environment, payments must be below 5 GBP / EUR. For details on any payment limits in Production, contact your Plaid Account Manager.
1610
1611        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/payment-initiation/#payment_initiationpaymentcreate>."""
1612        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1613        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1614        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1615            "recipient_id": recipient_id,
1616            "reference": reference,
1617            "amount": None if amount is None else amount.dict(),
1618            "schedule": None if schedule is None else schedule.dict(),
1619            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1620        }
1621        res = await self.send(
1622            "POST",
1623            self.base_url + "/payment_initiation/payment/create",
1624            headers,
1625            params,
1626            data,
1627        )
1628        data = await res.json()
1629        return model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)
1630

1633    ) -> model.PaymentInitiationPaymentTokenCreateResponse:
1634        """Create payment token
1635
1636        The `/payment_initiation/payment/token/create` endpoint has been deprecated. New Plaid customers will be unable to use this endpoint, and existing customers are encouraged to migrate to the newer, `link_token`-based flow. The recommended flow is to provide the `payment_id` to `/link/token/create`, which returns a `link_token` used to initialize Link.
1637
1638        The `/payment_initiation/payment/token/create` is used to create a `payment_token`, which can then be used in Link initialization to enter a payment initiation flow. You can only use a `payment_token` once. If this attempt fails, the end user aborts the flow, or the token expires, you will need to create a new payment token. Creating a new payment token does not require end user input.
1639
1640        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/link/maintain-legacy-integration/#creating-a-payment-token>."""

1956    async def asset_report_refresh(
1957        self,
1958        asset_report_token: str,
1959        days_requested: Optional[int] = None,
1960        options: Optional[model.AssetReportRefreshRequestOptions] = None,
1961    ) -> model.AssetReportRefreshResponse:
1962        """Refresh an Asset Report
1963
1964        An Asset Report is an immutable snapshot of a user's assets. In order to "refresh" an Asset Report you created previously, you can use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint to create a new Asset Report based on the old one, but with the most recent data available.
1965
1966        The new Asset Report will contain the same Items as the original Report, as well as the same filters applied by any call to `/asset_report/filter`. By default, the new Asset Report will also use the same parameters you submitted with your original `/asset_report/create` request, but the original `days_requested` value and the values of any parameters in the `options` object can be overridden with new values. To change these arguments, simply supply new values for them in your request to `/asset_report/refresh`. Submit an empty string ("") for any previously-populated fields you would like set as empty.
1967
1968        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportrefresh>."""
1969        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1970        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1971        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1972            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
1973            "days_requested": days_requested,
1974            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1975        }
1976        res = await self.send(

2023    async def asset_report_filter(
2024        self, asset_report_token: str, account_ids_to_exclude: List[str]
2025    ) -> model.AssetReportFilterResponse:
2026        """Filter Asset Report
2027
2028        By default, an Asset Report will contain all of the accounts on a given Item. In some cases, you may not want the Asset Report to contain all accounts. For example, you might have the end user choose which accounts are relevant in Link using the Account Select view, which you can enable in the dashboard. Or, you might always exclude certain account types or subtypes, which you can identify by using the `/accounts/get` endpoint. To narrow an Asset Report to only a subset of accounts, use the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint.
2029
2030        To exclude certain Accounts from an Asset Report, first use the `/asset_report/create` endpoint to create the report, then send the `asset_report_token` along with a list of `account_ids` to exclude to the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint, to create a new Asset Report which contains only a subset of the original Asset Report's data.
2031
2032        Because Asset Reports are immutable, calling `/asset_report/filter` does not alter the original Asset Report in any way; rather, `/asset_report/filter` creates a new Asset Report with a new token and id. Asset Reports created via `/asset_report/filter` do not contain new Asset data, and are not billed.
2033
2034        Plaid will fire a [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook once generation of the filtered Asset Report has completed.
2035
2036        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportfilter>."""
2037        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2038        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2039        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2040            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2041            "account_ids_to_exclude": account_ids_to_exclude,
2042        }
2043        res = await self.send(
2044            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/filter", headers, params, data
2045        )
2046        data = await res.json()
2047        return model.AssetReportFilterResponse.parse_obj(data)

2058
2059        By default, an Asset Report includes transaction descriptions as returned by the bank, as opposed to parsed and categorized by Plaid. You can also receive cleaned and categorized transactions, as well as additional insights like merchant name or location information. We call this an Asset Report with Insights. 2060

2070        }
2071        res = await self.send(
2072            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/get", headers, params, data

2586    async def transfer_authorization_create(
2587        self,
2588        type_: str,
2589        network: str,
2590        amount: str,
2591        ach_class: str,
2592        user: model.TransferAuthorizationUserInRequest,
2593        access_token: Optional[str] = None,
2594        account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2595        device: Optional[model.TransferAuthorizationDevice] = None,
2596        origination_account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2597        iso_currency_code: Optional[str] = None,
2598        user_present: Optional[bool] = None,
2599        payment_profile_id: Optional[str] = None,
2600    ) -> model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse:
2601        """Create a transfer authorization
2602
2603        Use the `/transfer/authorization/create` endpoint to determine transfer failure risk.
2604
2605        In Plaid's sandbox environment the decisions will be returned as follows:
2606
2607          - To approve a transfer with null rationale code, make an authorization request with an `amount` less than the available balance in the account.
2608
2609          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `MANUALLY_VERIFIED_ITEM`, create an Item in Link through the [Same Day Micro-deposits flow](https://plaid.com/docs/auth/coverage/testing/#testing-same-day-micro-deposits).
2610
2611          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `LOGIN_REQUIRED`, [reset the login for an Item](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/#item_login_required).
2612
2613          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `NSF`, the available balance on the account must be less than the authorization `amount`. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2614
2615          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `RISK`, the available balance on the account must be exactly $0. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2616
2617        For guaranteed ACH customers, the following fields are required : `user.phone_number` (optional if `email_address` provided), `user.email_address` (optional if `phone_number` provided), `device.ip_address`, `device.user_agent`, and `user_present`.
2618
2619        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transfer/#transferauthorizationcreate>."""
2620        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2621        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2622        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2623            "access_token": access_token,
2624            "account_id": account_id,
2625            "type": type,
2626            "network": network,
2627            "amount": amount,
2628            "ach_class": ach_class,
2629            "user": None if user is None else user.dict(),
2630            "device": None if device is None else device.dict(),
2631            "origination_account_id": origination_account_id,
2632            "iso_currency_code": iso_currency_code,
2633            "user_present": user_present,
2634            "payment_profile_id": payment_profile_id,
2635        }
2636        res = await self.send(
2637            "POST",
2638            self.base_url + "/transfer/authorization/create",
2639            headers,
2640            params,
2641            data,
2642        )
2643        data = await res.json()
2644        return model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

3515        `/income/verification/precheck` is an optional endpoint that can be called before initializing a Link session for income verification. It evaluates whether a given user is supportable by digital income verification and returns a `precheck_id` that can be provided to `/link/token/create`. If the user cannot be confirmed as eligible, the `precheck_id` can still be provided to `/link/token/create` and the user can still use the income verification flow, but they may be required to manually upload a paystub to verify their income.
3516
3517        While all request fields are optional, providing either `employer` or `transactions_access_tokens` data will increase the chance of receiving a useful result.
3518
3519        This endpoint has been deprecated; new integrations should use `/credit/payroll_income/precheck` instead.
3520
3521        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/income/#incomeverificationprecheck>."""
3522        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
3523        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
3524        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
3525            "user": None if user is None else user.dict(),
3526            "employer": None if employer is None else employer.dict(),
3527            "transactions_access_token": transactions_access_token,
3528            "transactions_access_tokens": transactions_access_tokens,
3529            "us_military_info": None
3530            if us_military_info is None
3531            else us_military_info.dict(),
3532        }
3533        res = await self.send(
3534            "POST",
3535            self.base_url + "/income/verification/precheck",
3536            headers,
3537            params,
3538            data,
3539        )
3540        data = await res.json()
3541        return model.IncomeVerificationPrecheckResponse.parse_obj(data)

4363    def __del__(self) -> None:
4364        try:
4365            loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
4366            if loop.is_running():
4367                loop.create_task(self.session.close())
4368            else:
4369                loop.run_until_complete(self.session.close())
4370        except Exception:
4371            pass
4372
4373    @classmethod
4374    def from_env(cls) -> "AsyncPlaidClient":
4375        env = os.environ["PLAID_ENV"]
4376        url = f"https://{env}.plaid.com"
4377        return cls(base_url=url, authenticator=PlaidAuthenticator.from_env())
class AsyncPlaidClient: 
  13class AsyncPlaidClient:
  14    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
  15        self.authenticator = authenticator
  16        self.base_url = base_url
  17        self.session = aiohttp.ClientSession(
  18            headers={
  19                "User-Agent": "plaid2/python/0.1.0",
  20                "Content-Type": "application/json",
  21            }
  22        )
  23
  24    async def send(
  25        self,
  26        method: str,
  27        url: str,
  28        headers: Dict[str, str],
  29        params: Dict[str, str],
  30        data: Dict[str, Any],
  31    ) -> aiohttp.ClientResponse:
  32        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
  33        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
  34        if do_debug:
  35            logger.debug(
  36                json.dumps(
  37                    dict(
  38                        method=method,
  39                        url=url,
  40                        headers=dict(**headers, **self.session.headers),
  41                        params=params,
  42                        json=data,
  43                    )
  44                )
  45            )
  46        async with self.session.request(
  47            method, url, headers=headers, params=params, json=data
  48        ) as res:
  49            if do_debug:
  50                data = dict(
  51                    status_code=res.status,
  52                    headers=dict(**res.headers),
  53                )
  54                try:
  55                    data["json"] = await res.json()
  56                except json.JSONDecodeError:
  57                    data["body"] = await res.text()
  58                logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
  59            if not res.ok:
  60                content = await res.text()
  61                res.release()
  62                raise aiohttp.ClientResponseError(
  63                    res.request_info,
  64                    res.history,
  65                    status=res.status,
  66                    message=content,
  67                    headers=res.headers,
  68                )
  69            return res
  70

 150    async def auth_get(
 151        self, access_token: str, options: Optional[model.AuthGetRequestOptions] = None
 152    ) -> model.AuthGetResponse:
 153        """Retrieve auth data
 154
 155        The `/auth/get` endpoint returns the bank account and bank identification numbers (such as routing numbers, for US accounts) associated with an Item's checking and savings accounts, along with high-level account data and balances when available.
 156
 157        Note: This request may take some time to complete if `auth` was not specified as an initial product when creating the Item. This is because Plaid must communicate directly with the institution to retrieve the data.
 158
 159        Also note that `/auth/get` will not return data for any new accounts opened after the Item was created. To obtain data for new accounts, create a new Item.
 160
 161        Versioning note: In API version 2017-03-08, the schema of the `numbers` object returned by this endpoint is substantially different. For details, see [Plaid API versioning](https://plaid.com/docs/api/versioning/#version-2018-05-22).
 162
 163        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/auth/#authget>."""
 164        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 165        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 166        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 167            "access_token": access_token,
 168            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 169        }
 170        res = await self.send(
 171            "POST", self.base_url + "/auth/get", headers, params, data
 172        )
 173        data = await res.json()
 174        return model.AuthGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 175
 176    async def transactions_get(
 177        self,
 178        access_token: str,
 179        start_date: str,
 180        end_date: str,
 181        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
 182    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
 183        """Get transaction data
 184
 185        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
 186
 187        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
 188
 189        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
 190
 191        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 192
 193        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
 194
 195        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
 196        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 197        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 198        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 199            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 200            "access_token": access_token,
 201            "start_date": start_date,
 202            "end_date": end_date,
 203        }
 204        res = await self.send(
 205            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
 206        )
 207        data = await res.json()
 208        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 209
 210    async def transactions_refresh(
 211        self, access_token: str
 212    ) -> model.TransactionsRefreshResponse:
 213        """Refresh transaction data
 214
 215        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
 216
 217        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
 218
 219        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
 220        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 221        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 222        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 223            "access_token": access_token,
 224        }
 225        res = await self.send(
 226            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
 227        )
 228        data = await res.json()

 231    async def transactions_recurring_get(
 232        self,
 233        access_token: str,
 234        account_ids: List[str],
 235        options: Optional[model.TransactionsRecurringGetRequestOptions] = None,
 236    ) -> model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse:
 237        """Fetch recurring transaction streams
 238
 239        The `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint allows developers to receive a summary of the recurring outflow and inflow streams (expenses and deposits) from a users checking, savings or credit card accounts. Additionally, Plaid provides key insights about each recurring stream including the category, merchant, last amount, and more. Developers can use these insights to build tools and experiences that help their users better manage cash flow, monitor subscriptions, reduce spend, and stay on track with bill payments.
 240
 241        This endpoint is not included by default as part of Transactions. To request access to this endpoint and learn more about pricing, contact your Plaid account manager.
 242
 243        Note that unlike `/transactions/get`, `/transactions/recurring/get` will not initialize an Item with Transactions. The Item must already have been initialized with Transactions (either during Link, by specifying it in `/link/token/create`, or after Link, by calling `/transactions/get`) before calling this endpoint. Data is available to `/transactions/recurring/get` approximately 5 seconds after the [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhook has fired (about 1-2 minutes after initialization).
 244
 245        After the initial call, you can call `/transactions/recurring/get` endpoint at any point in the future to retrieve the latest summary of recurring streams. Since recurring streams do not change often, it will typically not be necessary to call this endpoint more than once per day.
 246
 247        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrecurringget>."""
 248        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 249        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 250        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 251            "access_token": access_token,
 252            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 253            "account_ids": account_ids,
 254        }
 255        res = await self.send(
 256            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/recurring/get", headers, params, data
 257        )
 258        data = await res.json()
 259        return model.TransactionsRecurringGetResponse.parse_obj(data)
 260
 261    async def transactions_sync(
 262        self,
 263        access_token: str,
 264        cursor: Optional[str] = None,
 265        count: Optional[int] = None,
 266        options: Optional[model.TransactionsSyncRequestOptions] = None,
 267    ) -> model.TransactionsSyncResponse:
 268        """Get incremental transaction updates on an Item
 269
 270        This endpoint replaces `/transactions/get` and its associated webhooks for most common use-cases.
 271
 272        The `/transactions/sync` endpoint allows developers to subscribe to all transactions associated with an Item and get updates synchronously in a stream-like manner, using a cursor to track which updates have already been seen. `/transactions/sync` provides the same functionality as `/transactions/get` and can be used instead of `/transactions/get` to simplify the process of tracking transactions updates.
 273
 274        This endpoint provides user-authorized transaction data for `credit`, `depository`, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from `investments` accounts, use `/investments/transactions/get` instead.
 275
 276        Returned transactions data is grouped into three types of update, indicating whether the transaction was added, removed, or modified since the last call to the API.
 277
 278        In the first call to `/transactions/sync` for an Item, the endpoint will return all historical transactions data associated with that Item up until the time of the API call (as "adds"), which then generates a `next_cursor` for that Item. In subsequent calls, send the `next_cursor` to receive only the changes that have occurred since the previous call.
 279
 280        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. The `has_more` field specifies if additional calls are necessary to fetch all available transaction updates.
 281
 282        Whenever new or updated transaction data becomes available, `/transactions/sync` will provide these updates. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
 283
 284        Note that for newly created Items, data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/sync`. Plaid begins preparing transactions data when the Item is created, but the process can take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete, depending on the number of transactions available.
 285
 286        To be alerted when new data is available, listen for the [`SYNC_UPDATES_AVAILABLE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#sync_updates_available) webhook.
 287
 288        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionssync>."""
 289        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
 290        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
 291        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
 292            "access_token": access_token,
 293            "cursor": cursor,
 294            "count": count,
 295            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
 296        }
 297        res = await self.send(
 298            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/sync", headers, params, data
 299        )
 300        data = await res.json()
 301        return model.TransactionsSyncResponse.parse_obj(data)
 302

1285    async def processor_auth_get(
1286        self, processor_token: str
1287    ) -> model.ProcessorAuthGetResponse:
1288        """Retrieve Auth data
1289
1290        The `/processor/auth/get` endpoint returns the bank account and bank identification number (such as the routing number, for US accounts), for a checking or savings account that''s associated with a given `processor_token`. The endpoint also returns high-level account data and balances when available.
1291
1292        Versioning note: API versions 2019-05-29 and earlier use a different schema for the `numbers` object returned by this endpoint. For details, see [Plaid API versioning](https://plaid.com/docs/api/versioning/#version-2020-09-14).

1596    async def payment_initiation_payment_create(
1597        self,
1598        recipient_id: str,
1599        reference: str,
1600        amount: model.PaymentAmount,
1601        schedule: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentScheduleRequest] = None,
1602        options: Optional[model.ExternalPaymentOptions] = None,
1603    ) -> model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse:
1604        """Create a payment
1605
1606        After creating a payment recipient, you can use the `/payment_initiation/payment/create` endpoint to create a payment to that recipient.  Payments can be one-time or standing order (recurring) and can be denominated in either EUR or GBP.  If making domestic GBP-denominated payments, your recipient must have been created with BACS numbers. In general, EUR-denominated payments will be sent via SEPA Credit Transfer and GBP-denominated payments will be sent via the Faster Payments network, but the payment network used will be determined by the institution. Payments sent via Faster Payments will typically arrive immediately, while payments sent via SEPA Credit Transfer will typically arrive in one business day.
1607
1608        Standing orders (recurring payments) must be denominated in GBP and can only be sent to recipients in the UK. Once created, standing order payments cannot be modified or canceled via the API. An end user can cancel or modify a standing order directly on their banking application or website, or by contacting the bank. Standing orders will follow the payment rules of the underlying rails (Faster Payments in UK). Payments can be sent Monday to Friday, excluding bank holidays. If the pre-arranged date falls on a weekend or bank holiday, the payment is made on the next working day. It is not possible to guarantee the exact time the payment will reach the recipients account, although at least 90% of standing order payments are sent by 6am.
1609
1610        In the Development environment, payments must be below 5 GBP / EUR. For details on any payment limits in Production, contact your Plaid Account Manager.
1611
1612        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/payment-initiation/#payment_initiationpaymentcreate>."""
1613        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1614        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1615        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1616            "recipient_id": recipient_id,
1617            "reference": reference,
1618            "amount": None if amount is None else amount.dict(),
1619            "schedule": None if schedule is None else schedule.dict(),
1620            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1621        }
1622        res = await self.send(
1623            "POST",
1624            self.base_url + "/payment_initiation/payment/create",
1625            headers,
1626            params,
1627            data,
1628        )
1629        data = await res.json()
1630        return model.PaymentInitiationPaymentCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)
1631

1637        The `/payment_initiation/payment/token/create` endpoint has been deprecated. New Plaid customers will be unable to use this endpoint, and existing customers are encouraged to migrate to the newer, `link_token`-based flow. 1929    async def asset_report_create(
1930        self,

1934    ) -> model.AssetReportCreateResponse:

1936

1938
1939        The Asset Report takes some time to be created and is not available immediately after calling `/asset_report/create`. When the Asset Report is ready to be retrieved using `/asset_report/get` or `/asset_report/pdf/get`, Plaid will fire a `PRODUCT_READY` webhook. For full details of the webhook schema, see [Asset Report webhooks](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#webhooks).
1940
1941        The `/asset_report/create` endpoint creates an Asset Report at a moment in time. Asset Reports are immutable. To get an updated Asset Report, use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint.
1942
1943        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportcreate>."""
1944        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1945        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1946        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1947            "access_tokens": access_tokens,
1948            "days_requested": days_requested,
1949            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1950        }
1951        res = await self.send(
1952            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/create", headers, params, data
1953        )
1954        data = await res.json()
1955        return model.AssetReportCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

1957    async def asset_report_refresh(
1958        self,
1959        asset_report_token: str,
1960        days_requested: Optional[int] = None,
1961        options: Optional[model.AssetReportRefreshRequestOptions] = None,
1962    ) -> model.AssetReportRefreshResponse:
1963        """Refresh an Asset Report
1964
1965        An Asset Report is an immutable snapshot of a user's assets. In order to "refresh" an Asset Report you created previously, you can use the `/asset_report/refresh` endpoint to create a new Asset Report based on the old one, but with the most recent data available.
1966
1967        The new Asset Report will contain the same Items as the original Report, as well as the same filters applied by any call to `/asset_report/filter`. By default, the new Asset Report will also use the same parameters you submitted with your original `/asset_report/create` request, but the original `days_requested` value and the values of any parameters in the `options` object can be overridden with new values. To change these arguments, simply supply new values for them in your request to `/asset_report/refresh`. Submit an empty string ("") for any previously-populated fields you would like set as empty.
1968
1969        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportrefresh>."""
1970        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
1971        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
1972        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
1973            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
1974            "days_requested": days_requested,
1975            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
1976        }
1977        res = await self.send(
1978            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/refresh", headers, params, data
1979        )
1980        data = await res.json()
1981        return model.AssetReportRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)

2024    async def asset_report_filter(
2025        self, asset_report_token: str, account_ids_to_exclude: List[str]
2026    ) -> model.AssetReportFilterResponse:
2027        """Filter Asset Report
2028
2029        By default, an Asset Report will contain all of the accounts on a given Item. In some cases, you may not want the Asset Report to contain all accounts. For example, you might have the end user choose which accounts are relevant in Link using the Account Select view, which you can enable in the dashboard. Or, you might always exclude certain account types or subtypes, which you can identify by using the `/accounts/get` endpoint. To narrow an Asset Report to only a subset of accounts, use the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint.
2030
2031        To exclude certain Accounts from an Asset Report, first use the `/asset_report/create` endpoint to create the report, then send the `asset_report_token` along with a list of `account_ids` to exclude to the `/asset_report/filter` endpoint, to create a new Asset Report which contains only a subset of the original Asset Report's data.
2032
2033        Because Asset Reports are immutable, calling `/asset_report/filter` does not alter the original Asset Report in any way; rather, `/asset_report/filter` creates a new Asset Report with a new token and id. Asset Reports created via `/asset_report/filter` do not contain new Asset data, and are not billed.
2034
2035        Plaid will fire a [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook once generation of the filtered Asset Report has completed.
2036
2037        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportfilter>."""
2038        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2039        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2040        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2041            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2042            "account_ids_to_exclude": account_ids_to_exclude,
2043        }
2044        res = await self.send(
2045            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/filter", headers, params, data
2046        )
2047        data = await res.json()
2048        return model.AssetReportFilterResponse.parse_obj(data)

2055    ) -> model.AssetReportGetResponse:
2056        """Retrieve an Asset Report
2057
2058        The `/asset_report/get` endpoint retrieves the Asset Report in JSON format. Before calling `/asset_report/get`, you must first create the Asset Report using `/asset_report/create` (or filter an Asset Report using `/asset_report/filter`) and then wait for the [`PRODUCT_READY`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#product_ready) webhook to fire, indicating that the Report is ready to be retrieved.
2059
2060        By default, an Asset Report includes transaction descriptions as returned by the bank, as opposed to parsed and categorized by Plaid. You can also receive cleaned and categorized transactions, as well as additional insights like merchant name or location information. We call this an Asset Report with Insights. An Asset Report with Insights provides transaction category, location, and merchant information in addition to the transaction strings provided in a standard Asset Report.
2061
2062        To retrieve an Asset Report with Insights, call the `/asset_report/get` endpoint with `include_insights` set to `true`.
2063
2064        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/assets/#asset_reportget>."""
2065        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2066        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2067        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2068            "asset_report_token": asset_report_token,
2069            "include_insights": include_insights,
2070            "fast_report": fast_report,
2071        }
2072        res = await self.send(
2073            "POST", self.base_url + "/asset_report/get", headers, params, data
2074        )
2075        data = await res.json()
2076        return model.AssetReportGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

2587    async def transfer_authorization_create(
2588        self,
2589        type_: str,
2590        network: str,
2591        amount: str,
2592        ach_class: str,
2593        user: model.TransferAuthorizationUserInRequest,
2594        access_token: Optional[str] = None,
2595        account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2596        device: Optional[model.TransferAuthorizationDevice] = None,
2597        origination_account_id: Optional[str] = None,
2598        iso_currency_code: Optional[str] = None,
2599        user_present: Optional[bool] = None,
2600        payment_profile_id: Optional[str] = None,
2601    ) -> model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse:
2602        """Create a transfer authorization
2603
2604        Use the `/transfer/authorization/create` endpoint to determine transfer failure risk.
2605
2606        In Plaid's sandbox environment the decisions will be returned as follows:
2607
2608          - To approve a transfer with null rationale code, make an authorization request with an `amount` less than the available balance in the account.
2609
2610          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `MANUALLY_VERIFIED_ITEM`, create an Item in Link through the [Same Day Micro-deposits flow](https://plaid.com/docs/auth/coverage/testing/#testing-same-day-micro-deposits).
2611
2612          - To approve a transfer with the rationale code `LOGIN_REQUIRED`, [reset the login for an Item](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/#item_login_required).
2613
2614          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `NSF`, the available balance on the account must be less than the authorization `amount`. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2615
2616          - To decline a transfer with the rationale code `RISK`, the available balance on the account must be exactly $0. See [Create Sandbox test data](https://plaid.com/docs/sandbox/user-custom/) for details on how to customize data in Sandbox.
2617
2618        For guaranteed ACH customers, the following fields are required : `user.phone_number` (optional if `email_address` provided), `user.email_address` (optional if `phone_number` provided), `device.ip_address`, `device.user_agent`, and `user_present`.
2619
2620        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transfer/#transferauthorizationcreate>."""
2621        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
2622        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
2623        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
2624            "access_token": access_token,
2625            "account_id": account_id,
2626            "type": type,
2627            "network": network,
2628            "amount": amount,
2629            "ach_class": ach_class,
2630            "user": None if user is None else user.dict(),
2631            "device": None if device is None else device.dict(),
2632            "origination_account_id": origination_account_id,
2633            "iso_currency_code": iso_currency_code,
2634            "user_present": user_present,
2635            "payment_profile_id": payment_profile_id,
2636        }
2637        res = await self.send(
2638            "POST",
2639            self.base_url + "/transfer/authorization/create",
2640            headers,
2641            params,
2642            data,
2643        )
2644        data = await res.json()
2645        return model.TransferAuthorizationCreateResponse.parse_obj(data)

3517

3529            "transactions_access_tokens": transactions_access_tokens,
3530            "us_military_info": None
3531            if us_military_info is None
3532            else us_military_info.dict(),

3989            "device": None if device is None else device.dict(),
3990        }
3991        res = await self.send(

4364    def __del__(self) -> None:
4365        try:
4366            loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
4367            if loop.is_running():
4368                loop.create_task(self.session.close())
4369            else:
4370                loop.run_until_complete(self.session.close())
4371        except Exception:
4372            pass
4373
4374    @classmethod
4375    def from_env(cls) -> "AsyncPlaidClient":
4376        env = os.environ["PLAID_ENV"]
4377        url = f"https://{env}.plaid.com"
4378        return cls(base_url=url, authenticator=PlaidAuthenticator.from_env())
AsyncPlaidClient( base_url: str, authenticator: plaid2.authenticator.PlaidAuthenticator) 
14    def __init__(self, base_url: str, authenticator: PlaidAuthenticator) -> None:
15        self.authenticator = authenticator
16        self.base_url = base_url
17        self.session = aiohttp.ClientSession(
18            headers={
19                "User-Agent": "plaid2/python/0.1.0",
20                "Content-Type": "application/json",
21            }
22        )
async def send( self, method: str, url: str, headers: Dict[str, str], params: Dict[str, str], data: Dict[str, Any]) -> aiohttp.client_reqrep.ClientResponse: 
24    async def send(
25        self,
26        method: str,
27        url: str,
28        headers: Dict[str, str],
29        params: Dict[str, str],
30        data: Dict[str, Any],
31    ) -> aiohttp.ClientResponse:
32        self.authenticator.authenticate(headers, params, data)
33        do_debug = logger.getEffectiveLevel() == logging.DEBUG
34        if do_debug:
35            logger.debug(
36                json.dumps(
37                    dict(
38                        method=method,
39                        url=url,
40                        headers=dict(**headers, **self.session.headers),
41                        params=params,
42                        json=data,
43                    )
44                )
45            )
46        async with self.session.request(
47            method, url, headers=headers, params=params, json=data
48        ) as res:
49            if do_debug:
50                data = dict(
51                    status_code=res.status,
52                    headers=dict(**res.headers),
53                )
54                try:
55                    data["json"] = await res.json()
56                except json.JSONDecodeError:
57                    data["body"] = await res.text()
58                logger.debug(json.dumps(data))
59            if not res.ok:
60                content = await res.text()
61                res.release()
62                raise aiohttp.ClientResponseError(
63                    res.request_info,
64                    res.history,
65                    status=res.status,
66                    message=content,
67                    headers=res.headers,
68                )
69            return res

async def transactions_get( self, access_token: str, start_date: str, end_date: str, options: Optional[plaid2.model.transactions_get_request_options.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None) -> plaid2.model.transactions_get_response.TransactionsGetResponse: 
176    async def transactions_get(
177        self,
178        access_token: str,
179        start_date: str,
180        end_date: str,
181        options: Optional[model.TransactionsGetRequestOptions] = None,
182    ) -> model.TransactionsGetResponse:
183        """Get transaction data
184
185        The `/transactions/get` endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype `student`; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the [Investments endpoint](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/investments/) instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.
186
187        Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift.  Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in `/transactions/get`.  For more details, see [Pending and posted transactions](https://plaid.com/docs/transactions/transactions-data/#pending-and-posted-transactions).
188
189        Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the `count` and `offset` parameters in conjunction with the `total_transactions` response body field to fetch all available transactions.
190
191        Data returned by `/transactions/get` will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's `status.transactions.last_successful_update` field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the `/transactions/refresh` endpoint.
192
193        Note that data may not be immediately available to `/transactions/get`. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with `transactions`, or upon the first call to `/transactions/get`, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the [`INITIAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#initial_update) and [`HISTORICAL_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#historical_update) webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when `/transactions/get` is called, it will return a `PRODUCT_NOT_READY` error.
194
195        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget>."""
196        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
197        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
198        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
199            "options": None if options is None else options.dict(),
200            "access_token": access_token,
201            "start_date": start_date,
202            "end_date": end_date,
203        }
204        res = await self.send(
205            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/get", headers, params, data
206        )
207        data = await res.json()
208        return model.TransactionsGetResponse.parse_obj(data)

Get transaction data

The /transactions/get endpoint allows developers to receive user-authorized transaction data for credit, depository, and some loan-type accounts (only those with account subtype student; coverage may be limited). For transaction history from investments accounts, use the Investments endpoint instead. Transaction data is standardized across financial institutions, and in many cases transactions are linked to a clean name, entity type, location, and category. Similarly, account data is standardized and returned with a clean name, number, balance, and other meta information where available.

Transactions are returned in reverse-chronological order, and the sequence of transaction ordering is stable and will not shift. Transactions are not immutable and can also be removed altogether by the institution; a removed transaction will no longer appear in /transactions/get. For more details, see Pending and posted transactions.

Due to the potentially large number of transactions associated with an Item, results are paginated. Manipulate the count and offset parameters in conjunction with the total_transactions response body field to fetch all available transactions.

Data returned by /transactions/get will be the data available for the Item as of the most recent successful check for new transactions. Plaid typically checks for new data multiple times a day, but these checks may occur less frequently, such as once a day, depending on the institution. An Item's status.transactions.last_successful_update field will show the timestamp of the most recent successful update. To force Plaid to check for new transactions, you can use the /transactions/refresh endpoint.

Note that data may not be immediately available to /transactions/get. Plaid will begin to prepare transactions data upon Item link, if Link was initialized with transactions, or upon the first call to /transactions/get, if it wasn't. To be alerted when transaction data is ready to be fetched, listen for the INITIAL_UPDATE and HISTORICAL_UPDATE webhooks. If no transaction history is ready when /transactions/get is called, it will return a PRODUCT_NOT_READY error.

See endpoint docs at https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsget.

async def transactions_refresh( self, access_token: str) -> plaid2.model.transactions_refresh_response.TransactionsRefreshResponse: 
210    async def transactions_refresh(
211        self, access_token: str
212    ) -> model.TransactionsRefreshResponse:
213        """Refresh transaction data
214
215        `/transactions/refresh` is an optional endpoint for users of the Transactions product. It initiates an on-demand extraction to fetch the newest transactions for an Item. This on-demand extraction takes place in addition to the periodic extractions that automatically occur multiple times a day for any Transactions-enabled Item. If changes to transactions are discovered after calling `/transactions/refresh`, Plaid will fire a webhook: [`TRANSACTIONS_REMOVED`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactions_removed) will be fired if any removed transactions are detected, and [`DEFAULT_UPDATE`](https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#default_update) will be fired if any new transactions are detected. New transactions can be fetched by calling `/transactions/get`.
216
217        Access to `/transactions/refresh` in Production is specific to certain pricing plans. If you cannot access `/transactions/refresh` in Production, [contact Sales](https://www.plaid.com/contact) for assistance.
218
219        See endpoint docs at <https://plaid.com/docs/api/products/transactions/#transactionsrefresh>."""
220        headers: Dict[str, str] = {}
221        params: Dict[str, str] = {}
222        data: Dict[str, Any] = {
223            "access_token": access_token,
224        }
225        res = await self.send(
226            "POST", self.base_url + "/transactions/refresh", headers, params, data
227        )
228        data = await res.json()
229        return model.TransactionsRefreshResponse.parse_obj(data)
